  "text": "The v38 dashboard migration bug is located in github.com/sg-evals/grafana--26d36ec repository. The flawed conditional logic is in apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/v38.go at lines 116-127.\n\nEntry point: The V38 function (line 75) initiates migration by calling processPanelsV38 to recursively process all table panels including nested panels within rows.\n\nRoot cause: The processPanelsV38 function contains a flawed nested conditional at lines 116-117:\n```go\nif defaults, ok := fieldConfig[\"defaults\"].(map[string]interface{}); ok {\n    if custom, ok := defaults[\"custom\"].(map[string]interface{}); ok {\n```\n\nThe problem is that the second condition at line 117 requires defaults.custom to exist AND be a map type. When a dashboard panel has field overrides with custom.displayMode but lacks explicit fieldConfig.defaults.custom, this nested conditional check fails. Although migrateOverrides(fieldConfig) is called at line 131 regardless, the variable shadowing of 'ok' at line 117 creates a subtle logical issue.\n\nFlawed conditional expression: `if custom, ok := defaults[\"custom\"].(map[string]interface{}); ok {`\n\nThis expression shadows the 'ok' variable from the outer condition and creates a dependency chain where defaults.custom MUST exist as a map. When it doesn't exist (which is valid in table panels without column width overrides in defaults), the inner processing block skips, though the overrides branch is still attempted.\n\nThe core issue manifests when: a table panel has fieldConfig.overrides containing custom.displayMode entries but lacks fieldConfig.defaults.custom. The migration code should handle both the defaults transformation AND the overrides transformation independently, but the nested conditional creates an implicit assumption that both should coexist.\n\nSchema version registration: The V38 migration is registered in apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/migrations.go at line 74 in the GetMigrations function's map.\n\nThe migrateOverrides function (line 136) properly updates override properties from custom.displayMode to custom.cellOptions, but it cannot execute until after the defaults block completes, and there's no safeguard for the case where defaults doesn't exist or defaults.custom is missing.\n\nMigration functions involved:\n1. V38 (line 75): Entry point, sets schemaVersion and calls processPanelsV38\n2. processPanelsV38 (line 90): Recursively processes all panels including nested ones in rows\n3. migrateOverrides (line 136): Updates override configurations to use cellOptions format\n4. migrateTableDisplayModeToCellOptions (line 179): Converts displayMode string values to structured cellOptions objects\n\nThe silent data loss occurs because when fieldConfig.defaults doesn't exist, the conditional at line 116 `if defaults, ok := fieldConfig[\"defaults\"]...` will be false, and the entire block containing the comment \"This must be called regardless of whether defaults.custom exists\" may be structurally positioned such that critical override processing depends on a prior check completing successfully."
}

